# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mclean-virginia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] The **1950 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States to be 151,325,798, an increase of 14.5 percent over the 131,669,275 persons enumerated during the 1940 census.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] On April 1, 2022, the National Archives and Records Administration released scanned census enumeration sheets to the general public, in accordance with the 72 year rule.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] It is the most recent census to have full public availability.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] In addition, a sample of individuals were asked additional questions covering income, marital history, fertility, and other topics.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] Full documentation on the 1950 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] Microdata from the 1950 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] All identifiable information in the census became available in April 2022 upon the release of the images taken by the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] On April 1, 2022, 72 years after the census was taken, the National Archives and Records Administration released scanned census enumeration sheets to the general public.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] The census data was also made freely searchable by name on other websites.
[src:mclean-virginia/1950-u-s-census] Genealogy companies Ancestry and FamilySearch partnered to use AI and human volunteers to review an index of all names listed on the 1950 census forms.
[src:mclean-virginia/1960-u-s-census] The **1960 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States to be 179,323,175, an increase of 19 percent over the 151,325,798 persons enumerated during the 1950 census.
[src:mclean-virginia/1960-u-s-census] This was the first census in which all states recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:mclean-virginia/1960-u-s-census] This census's data determined the electoral votes for the 1964 and 1968 presidential elections.
[src:mclean-virginia/1960-u-s-census] This was also the last census in which New York was the most populous state.
[src:mclean-virginia/1960-u-s-census] Detroit lost 220,000 residents in the 1950s, which remains the record for the largest loss of population between two censuses.
[src:mclean-virginia/1960-u-s-census] Approximately 25% of households received a "long form" of the 1960 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:mclean-virginia/1960-u-s-census] Full documentation on the 1960 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:mclean-virginia/1960-u-s-census] Microdata from the 1960 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:mclean-virginia/1960-u-s-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2032.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] The **1970 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States to be 203,392,031, an increase of 13.4 percent over the 179,323,175 persons enumerated during the 1960 census.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] This was the first census since 1820 in which New York was not the most populous state—California overtook it in population in January 1963.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] This was also the first census in which all states recorded a population of over 300,000, and the first in which a city in the geographic South—Houston—recorded a population of over 1 million.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] Accurate racial census data was required by both the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965, and the 1970 Census changed to identify race on the basis of self-identification rather than by government census enumerators.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] Virtually all of the key items from the 1960 census were retained.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1970 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] These data were originally created and disseminated by DUALabs.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2042.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] California took over as the most populous state; New York had previously been ranked number one.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] While the entire country increased to more than 204 million persons, four states lost population, with West Virginia leading the list, down roughly 7 percent from 1960.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] On April 25, 1973, the Census Bureau announced the results of a reanalysis of the 1970 census.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] The report estimated that the census undercounted approximately 5.33 million people, for a net undercount rate of 2.5%.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] This would have made the population approximately 208.7 million.
[src:mclean-virginia/1970-united-states-census] Of those undercounted, an estimated 3.45 million were white, and 1.88 million were black.
[src:mclean-virginia/1980-u-s-census] The **1980 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States to be 226,545,805, an increase of 11.4% over the 203,184,772 persons enumerated during the 1970 census.
[src:mclean-virginia/1980-u-s-census] It was the first census in which a state—California—recorded a population of 20 million people, as well as the first in which all states recorded populations of over 400,000.
[src:mclean-virginia/1980-u-s-census] This was the first census to count Hispanic and Latino Americans as an ethnicity.
[src:mclean-virginia/1980-u-s-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 1980 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:mclean-virginia/1980-u-s-census] Full documentation on the 1980 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:mclean-virginia/1980-u-s-census] Microdata from the 1980 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:mclean-virginia/1980-u-s-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2052.
[src:mclean-virginia/1980-u-s-census] Between the 1980 census and the 1990 census, the United States population increased by approximately 22,164,837 or 9.8%.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] The **1990 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States to be 248,709,873, an increase of 9.8 percent over the 226,545,805 persons enumerated during the 1980 census.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 1990 census, which contained more than 100 questions.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 1990 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] It was the first census to designate "Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander" as a racial group separate from Asians.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] The census was also the first census to be directed by a woman, Barbara Everitt Bryant.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] To increase black participation in the 1990 United States census, the bureau recruited Bill Cosby, Magic Johnson, Alfre Woodard, and Miss America Debbye Turner as spokespeople.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2062.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] This was the first census since 1880 in which Chicago was not the second-largest city, having been overtaken by Los Angeles.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] As of the 2020 census, Los Angeles has remained the nation's second-largest city.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] This was also the first census in which Wyoming was the least populous state.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] The results of the 1990 census determined the number of seats that each state receives in the United States House of Representatives starting with the 1992 elections.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] Consequently, this affected the number of votes each state has in the Electoral College for the 1992 presidential election.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] Because of population changes, twenty-one states had changes in their number of seats.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] Eight states gained at least one seat, and thirteen states lost at least one seat.
[src:mclean-virginia/1990-united-states-census] The final result involved 19 seats being switched.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] McLean is home to many wealthy residents, such as diplomats, military, members of Congress, and high-ranking government officials, partially due to its proximity to Washington, D.C., the Pentagon, and the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] It is the location of Hickory Hill, the former home of Ethel Kennedy, the widow of Robert F.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] It is also the location of Salona, the former home of Light-Horse Harry Lee, the Revolutionary War hero.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The community received its name from John Roll McLean, the former publisher and owner of *The Washington Post*.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Along with Stephen Benton Elkins and French aristocrat Jean-Pierre Guenard, in 1902, he bought the charter for the Great Falls and Old Dominion Railroad.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Completed in 1906, it connected the area with Washington, D.C.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] McLean named a railroad station costing $1,500, of which $500 was raised locally, after himself, where the rail line (traveling on the present route of Old Dominion Drive) crossed the old Chain Bridge Road.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The community itself was founded in 1910, when the communities of Lewinsville and Langley merged.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] McLean is located on the Capital Beltway (Interstate 495) in Northern Virginia, central McLean is 8 miles (13 km) northwest of downtown Washington, D.C., and 9 miles (14 km) northeast of Fairfax, the county seat.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The community lies in the Piedmont upland on the west bank of the Potomac River.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The river forms the community's northern and eastern borders, and a number of its smaller tributaries flow north and northeast through the CDP.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] From west to east, these include Bull Neck Run, Scott Run, Dead Run, Turkey Run, and Pimmit Run.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] According to the United States Census Bureau, the CDP has a total area of 24.88 square miles (64.4 km2) of which 24.79 square miles (64.2 km2) is land and 0.09 square miles (0.23 km2) is water.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] As an inner suburb of Washington, D.C., McLean is a part of both the Washington Metropolitan Area and the larger Baltimore-Washington Metropolitan Area.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The CDP includes the unincorporated communities of Langley, Lewinsville, and West McLean.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] McLean has a humid climate (*Cfa*) and is in hardiness zone 7a.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] McLean was first listed as an unincorprated community in the 1950 U.S. census.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The community did not appear in the 1960 U.S. census.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] It was listed as a census designated place in the 1980 U.S. census.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] As of the 2020 census, McLean had a population of 50,773.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] 26.1% of residents were under the age of 18 and 20.1% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] For every 100 females there were 93.9 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 90.1 males age 18 and over.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] 99.3% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.7% lived in rural areas.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] There were 17,044 households in McLean, of which 40.2% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Of all households, 71.5% were married-couple households, 8.9% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 17.9% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] About 16.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] There were 17,948 housing units, of which 5.0% were vacant.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.1% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.2%.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] There were 17,063 households, out of which 39.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 70.5% were married couples living together, 2.4% had a male householder with no wife present, 6.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 21.2% were non-families.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Of all households, 18.0% were individuals, and 10.3% had someone who was 65 or older living alone.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The average household size was 2.80, and the average family size was 3.17.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The gender makeup of the community was 48.2% male and 51.8% female.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The median income for a household in the CDP was $164,888, and the median income for a family was $194,832.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Males had a median income of $132,714 versus $87,663 for females.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The per capita income for the CDP was $87,073.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] About 1.3% of families and 2.6% of the population were below the poverty line, including 2.6% of those under 18 and 3.2% of those 65 and older.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] As of 2012, 61.6% of the population over 16 was in the workforce.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] 0.4% was in the armed forces, and 61.2% was in the civilian workforce, with 58.4% employed and 2.9% unemployed.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The three industries employing the largest percentages of the working civilian labor force were: professional, scientific, and management, and administrative and waste management services (27.8%); educational services, health care, and social assistance (17.7%); and public administration (16.6%).
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The cost of living in McLean is very high; compared to a U.S. average of 100, the cost of living index for the community is 142.6.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] As of 2012, the median home value in the community was $908,000, the median selected monthly owner cost was $3,803 for housing units with a mortgage and $1,000+ for those without, and the median gross rent was $2,000+.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Mars and Geebo are among the companies based in McLean.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Many businesses in neighboring Tysons, particularly those east of Leesburg Pike (VA Route 7), have a McLean mailing address, because the US Postal Service boundary for West McLean (ZIP Code 22102) generally follows Leesburg Pike.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The headquarters of the Central Intelligence Agency is located in the Langley area of McLean, and the headquarters of the Office of the Director of National Intelligence is also located in McLean.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Department of Transportation's Turner-Fairbank Highway Research Center is also located down the street from the CIA headquarters.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Fairfax County Public Library operates the Dolley Madison Library in McLean.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The McLean Little League is also located in McLean.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] In 2005, the girls' All-Star softball team from McLean Little League won the Little League Softball World Series Championship in Portland, Oregon.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] MLL's girls' All-Star softball team has been the Little League Softball World Series runner-up twice, in 2004 and in 2013.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The Mount Daniel School Park, operated by The City of Falls Church, is physically within the McLean CDP.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] McLean residents are zoned to schools in the Fairfax County Public Schools.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Mount Daniel School of the Falls Church City Public Schools is in McLean.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The Capital Beltway, George Washington Memorial Parkway, Interstate 66, Dulles Access Road, Dolley Madison Boulevard/Chain Bridge Road, Georgetown Pike, and Old Dominion Drive all run through McLean.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The Washington Metro's Silver Line is southwest of downtown McLean.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Both the Silver and Orange lines physically enter the borders in between East Falls Church and West Falls Church.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] The McLean station on the Silver Line is in the McLean CDP but lies along VA Route 123 about two miles west of downtown McLean.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] Other Metro stations nearby include West Falls Church on the Orange Line, East Falls Church on both the Silver and Orange Lines, and the Tysons station on the Silver Line, which also has a McLean address.
[src:mclean-virginia/mclean-virginia] WMATA (Metrobus) and Fairfax Connector each have several bus routes traveling through McLean, including routes connecting downtown McLean with the McLean Metrorail station.
